crime_data <- crime_data[crime_data$Victim_Gender != "UNKNOWN", ]

INTRODUCTION

Link to dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/fatmanur12/crime-data

Variables: Disposition: The current status of the case (Closed or Open). Offender_Race: The race of the offender (e.g., BLACK, WHITE, ASIAN, etc.). Offender_Gender: The gender of the offender (MALE or FEMALE). Offender_Age: The age of the offender (numerical value). PersonType: Type of person involved in the case (e.g., VICTIM, REPORTING PERSON, INTERVIEW). Victim_Race: The race of the victim (e.g., BLACK, WHITE, ASIAN, etc.). Victim_Gender: The gender of the victim (MALE or FEMALE). Victim_Age: The age of the victim (numerical value). Victim_Fatal_Status: Indicates if the victim’s injuries were fatal or non-fatal. Report Type: Type of report filed (e.g., Supplemental Report, Incident Report). Category: The category of crime (e.g., Theft, Vandalism, Violence, etc.).

Observations: We are observing convicted criminal data within this dataset. Every observation is one criminal and thier details.

The motivation behind analysizing this dataset comes from me just searching on Kaggle.com for a dataset to do this project on. I saw this dataset and was immediately interested in it. I’m eager to find out any interesting details in this dataset.

VISUALIZATIONS

Scatterplot of Offender_Age vs Victim_Age (Colored by Category)

ggplot(crime_data, aes(x = Offender_Age, y = Victim_Age)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = Category)) +
  labs(title = "Scatterplot of Offender_Age vs Victim_Age",
       x = "Offender_Age", y = "Victim_Age")

Here we see a scatterplot of the ages of the offenders vs the age of the victims that are also colored by the category of crime that was committed. Just looking at this graph, it is hard to tell whether or not there’s a correlation between the offender’s and the victim’s ages. However, we can see that there are a few outliers in the data. Looking at the coloring, there’s mostly crimes in the category of violence that were committed, but with that being said, there’s no way of inferring a correlation with the category of crime and both or any of the ages present in this data. To conclude, there’s no way of telling exactly by looking at the scatterplot if there’s correlation between the offender’s and the victim’s ages, and if there’s a correlation between the category of crime and the two ages (offender and victim).

Boxplot of Offender_Age vs Offender_Gender

ggplot(crime_data, aes(x = Offender_Gender, y = Offender_Age)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = "Box Plot of Offender Gender vs Age", x = "Offender_Gender",
       "Offender_Age")

For the box plot of Offender Gender vs Age, this shows the age ranges of each gender of the offenders. We can see that there’s a bigger range of the ages of male offenders compared to the females. Male offenders also have a wider interquartile range than females, which means 50% of male ages range as low as females, but also they have higher ages too compared to the female’s interquartile range. In other words, there are more older men (compared to females) that are committing these crimes. What’s really interesting is that their median is about the same. Which tells us that on average males and females commit crimes at the age 34 years (just about).

DATA MANIPULATION

Let’s categorize the offender’s age into age groups and put it in a bar graph to see how many crimes were committed by which age group.

crime_data <- crime_data %>%
  mutate(Age_Group = case_when(
    Offender_Age < 18 ~ "Under 18",
    Offender_Age >= 18 & Offender_Age < 35 ~ "18-34",
    Offender_Age >= 35 & Offender_Age < 50 ~ "35-49",
    Offender_Age >= 50 ~ "50+"
  ))

ggplot(crime_data, aes(x = Age_Group)) +
  geom_bar(fill = "orange") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Offenders by Age Group") +
  theme_minimal()

This new graph gives a pretty interesting insight to this crime data. Yes, we’ve been able to see the ranges of ages of the offenders through a box plot, but this gives us front and center that 18-34 year olds are the most amount of offenders in this dataset. Thanks to this new graph, we’re able to see the clear concentration of offenses among younger individuals, specifically those aged 18-34. This suggests that offenders in this age group are disproportionately represented in the dataset compared to other age groups.

STATISTICAL ANALYSES

Pearson Correlation

cor.test(crime_data$Victim_Age, crime_data$Offender_Age, method = "pearson")
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  crime_data$Victim_Age and crime_data$Offender_Age
## t = 24.088, df = 6628, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.2614323 0.3057023
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.2837185

We are looking to see if there’s a correlation between the Victim_Age and Offender_Age. To start off, we have a p-value of < 2.2e-16 which tells me that the correlation is statistically significant. Then, having a correlation coefficient of 0.2834644 tells me that the correlation is positive, but weak. So in conclusion, the correlation between the victim ages and offender ages are statistically significant and weak, but a positive correlation.

Linear Regression

ggplot(crime_data, aes(x = Offender_Age, y = Victim_Age)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = Category)) +
  labs(title = "Scatterplot of Offender_Age vs Victim_Age",
       x = "Offender_Age", y = "Victim_Age") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

model <- lm(Offender_Age ~ Victim_Age, data = crime_data)
summary(model)

Now in this graph that we’ve seen before, we have a line of best fit in it. This allows me to see the middle of the graph, and it’s pretty much where I expected to see it. Now, let’s get into the actual values that are provided below the graph. Looking at these values I assembled the equation: y = 0.237898x + 25.450275 for line of best fit. This tells us that Victim_Age increases by 0.237898 for each year that goes by for Offender_Age. The y intercept doesn’t really make sense in this situation, so I’m ignoring that part.

T-test to see if there’s a difference in offender ages between victim genders

t.test(Offender_Age ~ Victim_Gender, data = crime_data)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  Offender_Age by Victim_Gender
## t = -1.3292, df = 5488.4, p-value = 0.1838
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group FEMALE and group MALE is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -1.0651589  0.2043724
## sample estimates:
## mean in group FEMALE   mean in group MALE 
##             34.46805             34.89845

In order to see if there’s a difference in offender ages between male and female victims, we look at the p-value, which is 0.1838. Since in this case, this p-value is bigger than 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. In other words there is no significant difference.
To also support this, the confidence interval [ -1.0651589, 0.2043724] contains a 0 within it, which means there’s no significant difference.

How can you use this dataset to draw conclusions about a larger population? This dataset provides great insights to crime patterns, but in order to generalize its findings into a larger population. We would need to statistically analyze this dataset. Like what we did within this project, inspecting the summary statistics, graphing variables against each other, manipulating data, correlation tests, linear regression, and t-testing will give us various insgihts to many angles within this dataset and others.

CONCLUSION

For Offender_Age vs Victim_Age: Looking at it’s scatterplot, we couldn’t really get an idea of it’s correlation. Thus we performed Pearson’s correlation test to figure out the correlation. Through Pearson’s correlation test I concluded that the correlation between Offender_Age and Victim_Age was statistically significant and also weak, but a positive correlation.
Also, since these two variables are the only numerical variables, we also did linear regression to see if the line of best fit means anything huge for this dataset. We didn’t get much, other than the actual equation of it (y = 0.237898x + 25.450275) and my interpretation of it.

For Offender_Age vs Offender_Gender Inspecting it’s box plot, we get an idea of the age ranges of male and female offenders. With this graph we concluded that males had a bigger interquartile range than females. Both genders have very similar median age, and females had more outlier ages than men did.

For the Distribution of Offenders by Age Group For this new column that I made, I made age groups for the offenders and sorted them accordingly. Then made a bar graph showing the results, and it was very interesting to see. I found out that in this dataset that 18-34 year olds were the most abundant to committing crimes.

For Offender_Age vs Victim_Age A t-test was conducted to see if there was a difference in offender age based on victim gender. After analyzing the t-test, the p-value and the confidence interval concluded that there is no significant difference between the offender ages of male and female victims.
